import Foundation

let sampleSites: [HeritageSite] = [


    HeritageSite(
        name: "Agra Fort",
        location: "Uttar Pradesh",
        images: ["agrafort"],
        category: .cultural,
        history: "Agra Fort stands as a majestic red sandstone fortress in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India, embodying the grandeur of Mughal architecture. Built primarily during the 16th and 17th centuries, it served as the main residence for Mughal emperors until 1638. Agra Fort originated from an earlier brick structure called Badalgarh, ruined by the time Mughal Emperor Akbar arrived in Agra in 1558. Akbar rebuilt it from 1565 to 1573 using red sandstone from Rajasthan's Barauli area, with 4,000 builders working daily; it combined defensive walls and luxurious palaces. Later, Shah Jahan added white marble structures like the Khas Mahal and Jahangiri Palace, transforming it into an imperial city, while it witnessed key events like Humayun's coronation in 1530 and Shah Jahan's imprisonment by Aurangzeb.",
        keyFeatures: ["Massive double ramparts over 20 meters high with circular bastions, battlements, and gates like Delhi Gate (with drawbridge and Elephant Gate) for impregnable defense", "Intricate palaces including Jahangiri Mahal (red sandstone), Diwan-i-Aam (public audience hall), Diwan-i-Khas (private hall), Shish Mahal (glass mosaics), and Musamman Burj offering Taj Mahal views.", "Blend of Mughal, Persian, Islamic, and Rajput styles with inlay work, floral designs, and hidden passages possibly linking to Taj Mahal and Fatehpur Sikri."],
        unescoReason: "Agra Fort was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 for its exceptional Mughal architecture and historical role as the empire's power center. It exemplifies a 16th-century fortress enclosing an imperial city with fairy-tale palaces, audience halls, and mosques by emperors like Shah Jahan.",
        entryFee: 600,
        recommendedHours: 3,
        latitude: 27.1795,
        longitude: 78.0211),

    HeritageSite(name: "Ajanta Caves", location: "Maharashtra", images: ["AjantaCaves"], category: .cultural, history: "Ajanta Caves represent one of India's most remarkable rock-cut Buddhist sites, nestled in a horseshoe-shaped ravine along the Waghora River in Maharashtra's Aurangabad district. Excavated in two phases—first from the 2nd century BCE to 1st century CE under Satavahana patronage, and second from around 460-480 CE during the Vakataka dynasty—they served as viharas (monasteries) and chaityas (prayer halls) for Buddhist monks. The caves originated during the Satavahana era (2nd century BCE–1st century CE), with early Hinayana caves like 9, 10, 12, 13 hewn as simple chaityas and viharas from basalt cliffs. A four-century hiatus followed before Vakataka king Harishena revived work around 460 CE, commissioning Mahayana caves (1-8, 11, 14-29) with elaborate sculptures and paintings under patrons like Varahadeva and Upendragupta; activity halted by 480 CE amid political turmoil.", keyFeatures: ["30 rock-cut caves (29 numbered plus unfinished ones) blending chaityas with stupas (e.g., Cave 26's vaulted hall) and viharas with monk cells, pillars, and facades adorned in Gupta-style architecture.", "World-famous murals depicting Jataka tales, Buddha's life, and daily scenes in vibrant frescoes using tempera on plaster, showcasing early Indian painting mastery with expressive figures and natural motifs.", "Intricate sculptures of Bodhisattvas, deities, and elephants at entrances, with horseshoe arches, ribbed vaults, and light-enhancing windows revealing advanced rock excavation techniques."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1983, Ajanta Caves are celebrated for their outstanding universal value as the finest surviving examples of ancient Indian rock-cut Buddhist art from the 2nd century BCE to 6th century CE. They illustrate the evolution of Buddhist thematic art, architecture, and painting during pivotal eras like Satavahana and Vakataka rule.", entryFee: 600, recommendedHours: 5, latitude: 20.5519, longitude: 75.7033),

    HeritageSite(name: "Archaeological Site of Nalanda Mahavihara", location: "Bihar", images: ["NalandaMahavihara"], category: .cultural, history: "Archaeological Site of Nalanda Mahavihara (Nalanda University ruins) represents the ancient ruins of one of the world's greatest centers of learning, located in Nalanda district, Bihar, India, spanning over 12 hectares with remnants of monasteries, temples, and stupas that once housed up to 10,000 students and 2,000 teachers from across Asia. Established around 427 CE by 5th-century Gupta emperor Kumaragupta I as a monastic university, Nalanda Mahavihara flourished for nearly 800 years, attracting scholars like Dharmapala and Silabhadra while receiving patronage from Pala dynasty kings like Devapala (9th century); it thrived as a hub for Mahayana Buddhism, Hindu, and Jain studies until 1193 CE when Turkish invader Bakhtiyar Khilji burned its vast library of 9 million manuscripts, leading to its abandonment, with formal excavations starting in 1915-1937 by ASI revealing its layered brick structures built progressively through donations and royal grants.", keyFeatures: ["Three massive monasteries (Uttar Bihar, Vapa, and others) with over 200 cells around open courtyards, ornate shrines, and meditation halls featuring terracotta plaques and intricate brickwork.", "Temple No. 3's towering stupa (originally 30m high) adorned with four colossal Buddha statues in niches, surrounded by smaller shrines and votive stupas from 6th-12th centuries.", "Vast library complexes like Ratnasagara with three multistory buildings (Dharma Gunj, Ratna Sagar, Ratnodadhi) that stored palm-leaf manuscripts on subjects from grammar to astronomy."], unescoReason: "Designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2016, Nalanda exemplifies the pinnacle of ancient Asian higher learning with its innovative monastic design, international scholarship drawing pilgrims from China, Tibet, and Korea, and profound influence on disseminating Buddhism, logic, medicine, and mathematics across continents for a millennium.", entryFee: 300, recommendedHours: 3, latitude: 25.1367, longitude: 85.4449),

    HeritageSite(name: "Buddhist Monuments at Sanchi", location: "Madhya Pradesh", images: ["BuddhistSanchi"], category: .cultural, history: "Buddhist Monuments at Sanchi comprise a remarkable hilltop complex of stupas, temples, pillars, and monasteries in Raisen district, Madhya Pradesh, India, showcasing early Buddhist architecture from the 3rd century BCE to the 12th century CE. Commissioned originally by Mauryan emperor Ashoka around 260 BCE as a simple hemispherical brick stupa enshrining Buddha's relics—post his Kalinga War conversion to Buddhism—the site expanded under Shunga rulers (2nd century BCE) who encased it in stone with balustrades and staircases, followed by Satavahanas (1st century BCE–CE) adding ornate toranas (gateways), Kushanas and Guptas (1st–5th centuries CE) contributing sculptures and temples like Temple 17, and later medieval additions until Buddhism's decline, with rediscovery in 1818 by General Taylor and full excavations by Alexander Cunningham.", keyFeatures: ["Great Stupa No. 1, a 120-foot diameter dome with harmika and chatra, encircled by intricately carved toranas depicting Jataka tales, elephants, and symbolic motifs without direct Buddha images using aniconism.", "Ashoka Pillar with four-lion capital (now in museums) bearing Schism Edict, plus smaller stupas (No. 2–3) containing relics of Buddha's disciples Sariputta and Mahamoggallana.", "Monasteries with cells, chaityas, and Gupta-era Temple 17 featuring octagonal designs alongside free-standing pillars and votive structures blending aniconic and iconic Buddhist art."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1989, Sanchi exemplifies the finest preserved early Buddhist art and architecture illustrating Buddhism's formative evolution from Ashokan times through successive dynasties, with its toranas and stupas representing masterful stone carving that narrates doctrinal stories and influenced pan-Asian Buddhist iconography.", entryFee: 250, recommendedHours: 3, latitude: 23.4793, longitude: 77.7396),

    HeritageSite(name: "Champaner-Pavagadh Archaeological Park", location: "Gujarat", images: ["ChampanerPava"], category: .cultural, history: "Champaner-Pavagadh Archaeological Park sprawls across the Panchmahal district of Gujarat, India, encompassing the historic city of Champaner at the foothills of the volcanic Pavagadh Hill rising 800 meters, founded in the 8th century by Chavda king Vanraj Chavda naming it after his general Champa, evolving into a strategic fortress under Hindu rulers before Sultan Mahmud Begada of Gujarat captured it in 1484 CE transforming Champaner into his grand capital by 1535 CE with vast fortifications, palaces, mosques, and water systems blending Islamic and indigenous styles, destroyed by Mughal emperor Akbar in 1593 yet preserving Chalcolithic sites, 14th-century Hindu hill forts, 15th-16th century Islamic urban fabric including 114 monuments like Jami Masjid modeled for later Indian mosques, alongside Hindu/Jain temples and living pilgrimage at Kalika Mata shrine, with ASI excavations and Baroda Heritage Trust efforts leading to UNESCO recognition in 2004.", keyFeatures: ["Jami Masjid, a majestic sandstone mosque exemplifying Indo-Islamic fusion with tall minarets, ribbed domes, carved pillars, and spacious courtyards influencing subsequent Gujarati architecture.", "Pavagadh Hill fortifications including Atak Gate, Lakhigiri Vav stepwell, and Kalika Mata Temple atop the peak, a Shakti Peeth drawing millions of pilgrims amid prehistoric caves and Jain temples.", "Citadel walls, granaries, tombs like Nagina Masjid, residential precincts, and innovative water harvesting vavs/stepwells amidst agricultural structures in a largely unexcavated 1328-ha landscape."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 2004, the park holds outstanding universal value as a complete pre-Mughal Islamic city with unexcavated prehistoric-to-medieval layers, showcasing harmonious Hindu-Muslim-Jain architecture, military ingenuity, and living cultural heritage in a dramatic volcanic setting that influenced Gujarat's regional sultanate styles.", entryFee: 300, recommendedHours: 4, latitude: 22.4843, longitude: 73.5330),

    HeritageSite(name: "Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus", location: "Maharashtra", images: ["ChhatrapatiShivaji"], category: .cultural, history: "Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus (formerly Victoria Terminus) dominates Mumbai's skyline as an iconic Victorian Gothic Revival railway station and headquarters of Central Railway, constructed between 1878 and 1887 to mark Queen Victoria's Golden Jubilee amid Bombay's explosive growth as India's premier port, designed by British architect F.W. Stevens with initial sketches by Axel Haig in exuberant Indo-Saracenic style blending Italian Gothic elements like pointed arches and ribbed vaults with Indian motifs such as chhatris, jalis, and tropical verandahs using local Kurla yellow basalt and buff limestone crafted by Indian masons over a decade at immense cost (1.6 million rupees), evolving from the modest Bori Bunder station to handle burgeoning rail traffic connecting the subcontinent while symbolizing colonial commercial triumph before renaming in 1996 honoring Maratha warrior king Shivaji.", keyFeatures: ["Majestic central dome over the booking hall flanked by octagonal towers, turrets, flying buttresses, and a prominent clock tower with Gothic spires, gargoyles shaped as mythical beasts, and polychrome stonework evoking Venetian palaces.", "Elaborate sculptural program featuring the Progress statue atop the dome, lion and tiger statues symbolizing imperial might, stained glass windows, and intricate friezes with floral jaalis, elephant capitals, and railway-themed carvings.", "Expansive train sheds with iron trusses spanning 33 tracks, U-shaped layout with two wings embracing a grand courtyard, and functional innovations like high ceilings for ventilation suited to Mumbai's climate."], unescoReason: "Designated a World Heritage Site in 2004, it exemplifies outstanding Victorian Gothic Revival architecture fused with Indian traditions, representing the zenith of 19th-century railway engineering that catalyzed Mumbai's metamorphosis into Asia's busiest terminus while pioneering a syncretic Bombay Gothic style influencing colonial public buildings across India.", entryFee: 100, recommendedHours: 2, latitude: 18.9398, longitude: 72.8355),

    HeritageSite(name: "Churches and Convents of Goa", location: "Goa", images: ["Churchesgoa"], category: .cultural, history: "Churches and Convents of Goa form a stunning serial ensemble of seven religious monuments clustered in Old Goa (Goa Velha), once the thriving capital of the Portuguese Indies from 1565 known as the Rome of the East for its fervent Christian evangelization across Asia, with construction spanning the 16th-17th centuries under Portuguese colonial rule following Afonso de Albuquerque's conquest in 1510: the Chapel of St. Catherine (1510) commemorates the victory on St. Catherine's Day and was elevated to cathedral in 1534; Church of Our Lady of the Rosary (1549) as the earliest Manueline survivor; Basilica of Bom Jesus (1594-1605) enshrining St. Francis Xavier's incorrupt remains brought from China in 1613 with its rusted-gold façade by Japanese artisans; Se Cathedral (1562-1652) as Asia's largest church built post-1560 Protestant destruction using laterite stone in Tuscan exterior with Baroque interiors; Church and Convent of St. Francis of Assisi (1517, rebuilt 1661) blending Gothic-Manueline-Baroque; Church of St. Cajetan (1661) modeled after St. Peter's Rome; and the towering ruins of St. Augustine (1602) whose 46m belfry endures after collapse in 1842, all crafted by Augustinian, Franciscan, Dominican orders using local laterite, lime plaster, and Indo-Portuguese adaptations amid Goa's humid climate while disseminating European Renaissance art to missionary outposts in Japan, China, and beyond until Portuguese exit in 1961.", keyFeatures: ["Basilica of Bom Jesus' ornate façade with twisted columns, barrel-vaulted nave, and gilded wood carvings housing St. Francis Xavier's silver-encased relics in a glass-fronted tomb.", "Se Cathedral's massive 56m x 23m nave, Tuscan exterior, gilded altarpiece with the Miracle of the Cross painting, and giant bell from 1652 melt-down.", "St. Francis Assisi's barrel-vaulted interiors with wood-ribbed ceilings, late-Gothic motifs, Baroque altars painted with 24 Old Testament scenes, and adjacent museum."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1986, these monuments exemplify the pinnacle of Indo-Portuguese architecture fusing Manueline, Mannerist, and Baroque styles adapted to Asian contexts, profoundly influencing missionary art across Asia while illustrating 16th-18th century Christian evangelization from Goa's strategic colonial hub.", entryFee: 200, recommendedHours: 3, latitude: 15.5000, longitude: 73.9110),

    HeritageSite(name: "Dholavira", location: "Gujarat", images: ["Dholavira"], category: .cultural, history: "Dholavira stands as a grand Harappan city ruins on Khadirbet island in the Great Rann of Kutch, Gujarat, India—one of the largest Indus Valley sites spanning 100 hectares and thriving continuously from around 3000 BCE in its pre-Harappan phase through seven evolutionary stages to its peak circa 2500-2000 BCE as a sophisticated urban center with advanced water management amid arid conditions, discovered accidentally in the 1960s by local resident Shambhudan Gadhvi before official ASI recognition in 1967-68 by J.P. Joshi, with systematic excavations from 1990-2005 led by archaeologist R.S. Bisht uncovering a meticulously planned citadel (Castle), middle town (Bailey), lower town, and artisan quarters divided by massive sandstone walls up to 9m high with six gated entrances, reservoirs capturing seasonal Manasarovar lake runoff via 16+ stepwells and dams demonstrating unparalleled hydrological engineering, trade artifacts like Mesopotamian carnelian beads, copper tools, gold/silver ornaments, terracotta seals, and the world's earliest deciphered signboard featuring 10 large Indus script symbols, trade links to Rajasthan/Sindh/Punjab/Western Asia indicated by imported vessels and bead factories, declining post-1500 BCE with partial reoccupation in circular bhungas until abandonment likely due to climate shifts before full rediscovery highlighting its role as the Harappan civilization's westernmost flourishing outpost.", keyFeatures: ["Exceptional water conservation system with 16 reservoirs, dams, and channels storing monsoon runoff in a parched region, including the vast North-East reservoir and stepwells showcasing urban planning genius.", "Citadel's acropolis with elite residences, granaries, assembly halls, and stone-paved streets flanked by middle/lower towns with craft workshops, circular houses in later phases, and impressive East/North Gates with watchtowers.", "Archaeological treasures like the unique 10-symbol signboard, giant pottery jars, bronze vessels, intricate bead-making factories, and fortifications revealing industrial prowess and long-distance trade."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 2021, Dholavira exemplifies the Harappan civilization's zenith through its intact urban layout, innovative water harvesting, continuous cultural evolution over 1500 years from pre- to post-Harappan phases, and evidence of sophisticated trade, craftsmanship, and adaptation that enriched understandings of one of humanity's earliest urban societies.", entryFee: 250, recommendedHours: 4, latitude: 23.8887, longitude: 70.2177),

    HeritageSite(name: "Elephanta Caves", location: "Maharashtra", images: ["ElephantaCaves"], category: .cultural, history: "Elephanta Caves grace Elephanta Island (Gharapuri) in Mumbai Harbour, Maharashtra, India—a cluster of seven Hindu rock-cut caves primarily from the mid-5th to 6th century CE during the Konkan Mauryas or Traikutakas era, with later 7th-8th century Buddhist caves, hewn directly from volcanic basalt Deccan Traps rock by skilled artisans using chisels and hammers in a cruciform layout facing the Arabian Sea, possibly commissioned by local kings like Dantidurga of the Rashtrakutas who claimed patronage via inscriptions, evolving from 2nd century BCE Buddhist occupations evidenced by stupas to peak Shaivite devotion showcasing Pashupata Shaivism theology through monumental sculptures amid maritime trade hubs, suffering Portuguese iconoclasm in 1534-1540 when sailors defaced carvings with graffiti before British-era documentation and ASI conservation from 1978 restoring the main Cave 1 as Asia's finest Shiva temple exemplifying post-Gupta rock-cut mastery.", keyFeatures: ["Cave 1's grand 39m x 18m mandapa with 24m-high ceiling supported by four-pillared shrine and six rows of monolithic columns, housing the iconic 6m Trimurti Sadashiva (three-faced Shiva as Creator-Preserver-Destroyer).", "Dramatic relief panels like Gangadhara (Shiva receiving Ganges), Ardhanarishvara (half-male half-female Shiva-Parvati), Nataraja (cosmic dancer), Ravananugraha (Shiva pinning Ravana), and Yogishvara (ascetic Shiva) blending sculpture with architecture.", "Secondary caves (2-5, 7-8) with shrines, halls, and fragmented Shaivite panels plus eastern Buddhist viharas and chaityas featuring stupas from 5th-10th centuries."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1987, Elephanta Caves represent a masterpiece of human creative genius in Indian rock-cut architecture, bearing exceptional testimony to Shaivite cultural traditions through their unparalleled sculptural iconography that profoundly influenced Hindu temple design across western India.", entryFee: 600, recommendedHours: 3, latitude: 18.9633, longitude: 72.9315),

    HeritageSite(name: "Ellora Caves", location: "Maharashtra", images: ["ElloraCave"], category: .cultural, history: "Ellora Caves encompass a breathtaking tri-faith rock-cut complex in Aurangabad district, Maharashtra, India—34 caves (numbered 1-34) excavated sideways into the Charanandri Hills' basalt cliffs between the 6th and 10th centuries CE under successive Rashtrakuta and Yadava dynasties, beginning with 12 Buddhist viharas and chaityas (c.600-800 CE) patronized by Chalukya kings like Pulakeshin II, followed by 17 Hindu caves peaking with the colossal Kailasa Temple (Cave 16, c.760 CE) carved top-down by over 7,000 laborers under Rashtrakuta king Krishna I who excavated 200,000 tons of rock in a U-shaped monolithic horseshoe removing 400,000 cubic tons over 18 years to create a 1:1 replica of Mt. Kailash dedicated to Shiva, then 5 Jain caves (c.800-1000 CE) under Yadavas reflecting Digambara tradition, all demonstrating interfaith harmony as Hindu kings supported Buddhist and Jain excavations alongside their Shaivite masterpieces amid Deccan trade prosperity.", keyFeatures: ["Kailasa Temple's three-story 32m-high monolith with gopuram entrance, Nandi mandapa, towering shikhara, and freestanding courtyard walls adorned with Ramayana/Mahabharata friezes, Ravana shaking Kailash, and life-size elephants carved from living rock.", "Cave 32's (Jain Indra Sabha) ornate two-story vihara with 16 pillars, Manastambhas, and seated tirthankaras like Mahavira amid lush foliage carvings contrasting Buddhist Cave 10's simple chaitya with stupa.", "Multi-religious sculptures including Buddhist Padmapani Bodhisattva (Cave 11), Shiva slaying Andhaka (Cave 29), and Ravananugraha panels showcasing post-Gupta stylistic evolution from serene to dynamic figures."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1983, Ellora exemplifies unparalleled rock-cut architecture across Buddhism, Hinduism, and Jainism within a single site, with Kailasa as the world's largest monolithic temple illustrating Dravidian engineering genius and Rashtrakuta devotion while evidencing centuries of religious tolerance and artistic syncretism.", entryFee: 600, recommendedHours: 5, latitude: 20.0268, longitude: 75.1790),

    HeritageSite(name: "Fatehpur Sikri", location: "Uttar Pradesh", images: ["FatehpurSikri"], category: .cultural, history: "Fatehpur Sikri sprawls as a deserted Mughal ghost city 40km west of Agra in Uttar Pradesh, India—a meticulously planned red sandstone imperial capital founded in 1569-1571 by Emperor Akbar after his pilgrimage to Sufi saint Sheikh Salim Chishti at Sikri village who prophesied the birth of Akbar's heir Jahangir (Salim) following years of childlessness, rapidly constructed over 1571-1585 as Akbar's visionary Dinpanah (City of Refuge) blending Persian urban grid planning with indigenous Rajput and Gujarati motifs using local quarried red sandstone and white marble crafted by 36,000 artisans into fortified palaces, harems, audience halls, mosques, and gardens exemplifying Akbar's Sulh-i-Kul religious tolerance through Hindu-Muslim architectural fusion, thriving as administrative/judicial center until acute water scarcity from failing Sikri ridge wells amid expanding population forced Akbar to relocate the court back to Agra in 1585 leaving the pristine complex abandoned yet intact for British rediscovery and ASI protection.", keyFeatures: ["Buland Darwaza, the world's tallest victory gateway at 54m high built 1602 in red sandstone-marble inlay commemorating Gujarat conquest, with Quranic inscriptions and 42 steps symbolizing Akbar's triumph.", "Panch Mahal's ethereal five-story hypostyle pleasure pavilion diminishing from 84 columns below to open chhatri above, Diwan-i-Khas with central Akbar throne pillar unfolding into lotus petals, and Jodha Bai Palace blending Rajput harem aesthetics with Islamic courtyards.", "Jama Masjid's vast courtyard embracing Salim Chishti's pearl-white marble mausoleum filigreed with jali screens where pilgrims tie threads for fertility wishes, alongside Hiran Minar hunting tower and Turkish Sultana's octagonal diwan."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1986, Fatehpur Sikri bears exceptional testimony to 16th-century Mughal civilization through Akbar's syncretic architecture fusing Islamic-Persian-Hindu-Jain elements in a uniform red sandstone palette, exemplifying an imperial planned city that lasted only 14 years yet perfected courtyard typology influencing later Mughal capitals like Lahore and Shahjahanabad.", entryFee: 600, recommendedHours: 4, latitude: 27.0937, longitude: 77.6603),

    HeritageSite(name: "Great Living Chola Temples", location: "Tamil Nadu", images: ["CholaTemple"], category: .cultural, history: "Great Living Chola Temples comprise three magnificent 11th-12th century granite masterpieces in Tamil Nadu, India—Brihadisvara Temple at Thanjavur (completed 1010 CE by Rajaraja I with its 66m 13-tiered vimana as the world's tallest monolithic tower built without scaffolding using interlocking granite blocks and capstone dragged up ramps by elephants), Brihadisvara at Gangaikonda Cholapuram (1035 CE by Rajendra I commemorating Ganges conquest with 53m vimana, frescoed interiors, and Nandi mandapa), and Airavatesvara at Darasuram (12th century by Rajaraja II featuring chariot-shaped mandapa with 156 miniature dancers and wheel motifs)—erected during Chola Empire's imperial zenith when kings ruling from Thanjavur expanded maritime trade to Southeast Asia funding Shaivite devotion through innovative Dravidian architecture blending soaring pyramidal vimanas, colossal colonnaded halls, wall frescoes depicting Chola victories and Shiva myths, bronze Nataraja icons, and sacred tanks amidst fortified enclosures that continue daily worship rituals over a millennium later.", keyFeatures: ["Thanjavur Brihadisvara's 3.8m monolithic Nandi statue, vast frescoed walls with Chola royal portraits, and 81-foot lingam in gold-plated sanctum accessed via high plinth with lion motifs.", "Gangaikonda Cholapuram's octagonal shikhara, lion-base vimana, and intricate wall sculptures of pot-bellied dwarfs alongside river-inspired water motifs celebrating Rajendra's northern campaigns.", "Darasuram's Rajagambhira mandapa resembling a stone chariot drawn by caparisoned elephants, with animated figurines of musicians, dancers, and mythical beasts showcasing Chola sculptural virtuosity."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1987 (Thanjavur) and extended 2004, these living temples exemplify the apogee of Chola architectural-sculptural genius in Dravidian style, demonstrating progressive stylistic evolution across three royal capitals while preserving continuous thousand-year worship traditions that embody Tamil Shaivite culture and imperial Chola history.", entryFee: 300, recommendedHours: 4, latitude: 10.7828, longitude: 79.1311),

    HeritageSite(name: "Group of Monuments at Hampi", location: "Karnataka", images: ["GroupOfHampi"], category: .cultural, history: "Group of Monuments at Hampi sprawls across the Tungabhadra River basin in Karnataka's Ballari district, India—as the ruined capital Vijayanagara of the Vijayanagara Empire founded in 1336 CE by Sangama brothers Harihara I and Bukka Raya I following Delhi Sultanate incursions, rapidly expanding under Deva Raya II into a prosperous cosmopolitan hub whose 16th-century peak dazzled Portuguese traveler Domingo Paes as larger than Rome with 90-foot walls encircling 1600+ monuments blending Dravidian Hindu temple architecture with Indo-Islamic palace styles across sacred, royal, and urban zones amidst dramatic granite boulder-strewn landscapes, thriving on diamond/spice trade until catastrophic defeat at the 1565 Battle of Talikota by Deccan Sultanates unleashed eight-month sacking that abandoned the city overnight leaving pristine ruins rediscovered by Colonel Colin Mackenzie in 1800 and protected by ASI since 1986.", keyFeatures: ["Virupaksha Temple's towering 52m nine-story gopuram, living Shiva shrine with pinhole sub-shrines projecting temple image via optics, and sacred river tank sustaining continuous worship.", "Vittala Temple's iconic stone chariot shrine on wheels (actually fixed Garuda shrine), musical pillars resonating distinct notes when struck, and lotus-scalloped Kalyana mandapa columns.", "Royal Center's Mahanavami Dibba stepped platform for Dasara festivals overlooking Elephant Stables' domed Islamic pavilions, Hazara Rama Temple's Ramayana bas-reliefs on enclosure walls, and massive monolithic Lakshmi Narasimha statue."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1986, Hampi exemplifies Vijayanagara's architectural apogee through masterful Dravidian stone carving, urban planning harmonizing fortified palaces with temple complexes amid spectacular boulder landscapes, bearing unique testimony to the empire's cultural-economic zenith before its cataclysmic destruction.", entryFee: 500, recommendedHours: 6, latitude: 15.3350, longitude: 76.4600),

    HeritageSite(name: "Group of Monuments at Mahabalipuram", location: "Tamil Nadu", images: ["Mahabalipuram"], category: .cultural, history: "Group of Monuments at Mahabalipuram grace the Coromandel Coast in Tamil Nadu, India as a stunning Pallava dynasty ensemble (7th-8th centuries CE) at ancient port Mamallapuram founded by king Narasimhavarman I (Mamalla) who named it after his title, showcasing transitional Dravidian architecture evolution from rock-cut caves to freestanding structural temples: five monolithic rathas (chariot-shaped shrines dedicated to Shiva, Vishnu, and others carved 630-668 CE from single granite boulders), open-air mandapas like Krishna, Mahishasuramardini, and Varaha caves with mythological bas-reliefs, the colossal Descent of the Ganges (Arjuna's Penance) rock relief depicting 140+ figures including gods/elephants/celestial beings, and twin Shore Temples (c.700-728 CE by Rajasimha/Narasimhavarman II) as India's oldest surviving stone seaside shrines—one Shiva, one Vishnu—built atop sea-eroded promontory using granite blocks against Bay of Bengal waves, all evidencing Pallava experimentation blending Shaiva-Vaishnava-Shakta iconography that influenced Southeast Asian temple styles amid maritime trade prosperity before Chola conquest.", keyFeatures: ["Pancha Rathas' five distinct monolithic temples (Dharmaraja, Bhima, Arjuna, Nakula-Sahadeva, Draupadi) showcasing experimental vimana evolution from curvilinear to pyramidal forms with lion/yali motifs.", "Descent of the Ganges bas-relief (27m x 9m)—world's largest open-air rock sculpture—depicting Arjuna's penance or Bhagiratha's Ganges quest with split fissure symbolizing river amid elephants/gods/monkeys.", "Shore Temple's harmonious Shiva-Vishnu duality with pyramidal vimanas, Nandi/lion guardians, and moonstone steps surviving tsunamis as Pallava maritime devotion testament."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1984, Mahabalipuram exemplifies early Pallava artistic genius through diverse rock-