    HeritageSite(name: "Group of Monuments at Pattadakal", location: "Karnataka", images: ["Pattadakal"], category: .cultural, history: "Group of Monuments at Pattadakal nestles on the Malaprabha River banks in Bagalkot district, Karnataka, India—as a Chalukya dynasty coronation complex (7th-8th centuries CE) where kings like Vikramaditya II were crowned amid 10 major temples blending Nagara (northern curvilinear shikharas) and Dravidian (southern pyramidal vimanas) styles in a unique synthesis: Virupaksha Temple (c.740 CE) by Queen Lokamahadevi celebrating Vikramaditya's southern victories with three-tiered vimana, closed hall, elephant-adorned gateways, and frescoed Ramayana panels; Sangameshwara (c.725 CE) as Chalukya's largest early Shiva shrine; Mallikarjuna by Trilokamahadevi; Papanatha with Nagara superstructure; Kashi Vishveshvara, Galaganatha, and Jain Sangameshwara Temple showcasing hybrid experimentation by Chalukya artisans from nearby Badami/Aihole workshops using sandstone for intricate friezes of Shiva myths, dancers, and processions during Deccan empire's cultural zenith before Rashtrakuta conquest, preserved as active worship sites with towering Nandi mantapas.", keyFeatures: ["Virupaksha Temple's expansive three-tiered Dravidian vimana rising 30m with sukanasa niche, Nandi pavilion facing through ornate columns, and rear Kalyana mandapa for divine weddings carved with Saptamatrikas.", "Papanatha Temple's rare Nagara rekhanagara tower atop Dravidian base, Jambulingeswara's Nataraja sukanasa arch, and monolithic victory pillars bearing Sanskrit inscriptions of Chalukya triumphs.","Galaganatha Temple's staggered shikhara clusters and Chandraseshara's flat-roof simplicity contrasting Jain Narayana Temple's hybrid mandapa-shikhara dedicated to tirthankaras."], unescoReason: "Inscribed in 1987, Pattadakal represents the Chalukya era's architectural climax harmoniously fusing northern-southern Indian styles in a single sacred complex, exemplifying experim